--- body ---
## Context
Ticket 0182 fortified the manuscript claim (A.1 tripod / A.5) that the
three pre-2007 intellectual traditions were structurally separate. The
worry was low power: the pre-2007 co-citation graph is the sparsest slice
of the corpus (coverage diagnostic: 1344 works, only 30% carry any
outgoing edge, median references per work = 0, grey literature 2/1344),
so co-citation would show separation almost regardless. A degree-
preserving configuration-model null rules this out. Two labellings of the
same graph were tested (0182 dual run, N = 1000, seed 42, n_truncated = 0):

- **a_priori_anchors** — the load-bearing, non-circular test. Seed-sets
  fixed from the @tbl-traditions authors, assigned by first-author match
  with NO community detection anywhere. Induced subgraph 16 anchor-author
  nodes, 33 edges. Within-tradition co-citation share: observed 0.848 vs
  null 0.608 ± 0.033 (z = 7.2, empirical p = 0.001). 3-partition
  modularity: observed 0.169 vs null -0.037 ± 0.033 (z = 6.2, p = 0.001).
- **louvain_anchored** — reported for comparison only. Seed-sets are the
  Louvain communities the figure anchors (84 nodes, 369 edges); share
  observed 0.889 vs null 0.374 (z = 25.5), modularity 0.554 vs -0.012
  (z = 28.0). These overstate the historical claim because Louvain
  maximises modularity on the very graph the null tests.

Verdict FORTIFIED: even under strict a-priori labelling, the observed
separation exceeds the sparsity-conditioned null on both statistics
(z ≈ 6-7, p at the N = 1000 floor). The effect is much weaker than the
Louvain-anchored figure — the honest reading is that the separation is
real but modest once the labelling is kept clean of the graph's own
structure. A.5 states the a-priori result, not the z ≈ 26 Louvain figure.

